<div type="edition" xml:lang="tam-Latn" rendition="class:tamil maturity:vernacular">

<p>
<lb n="1"/>ṭaiyārkku Ippaḻuvūr Irukkum
<lb n="2"/>maṉṟāṭi Aṇitīraṉcolai A
<lb n="3"/>kola koṉṟa muttaṉai kāri
<lb n="4"/>Aṇitīraṉcolai korai cīrāḷ
<lb n="5"/>tevarkku cantirātittavaṟ Iravum
<lb n="6"/>vaitta cāvāmūvāp perāṭu
<lb n="7"/> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <hi rend="grantha">śva</hi>ra ra<hi rend="grantha">kṣai</hi> ||
</p>

</div>

<div type="apparatus">

</div>

<div type="translation" source="bib:Gillet2024_01">

<p>If we put the two fragments (#65 &amp; #66) together we have the following text, for which I propose a tentative translation (it may refer to a donation of goat for a lamp for someone who died):</p><p>{nothing} <g type="kaḻañcu"/> (1) ṭaiyārkku ˚ippaḻuvūr ˚irukkum</p><p>(1) {unlegible} <g type="kaḻañcu"/> (2) maṉṟāṭi ˚aṇitiraṉ colai ˚a</p><p>(2) yāṉ muttaṉ [korai] cirāḷḷai paṭa X <g type="kaḻañcu"/> (3) kola koṉṟa muttaṉai kāri</p><p>(3) ṭṭamāṭṭātu ˚avaṉ taṅkaḷ nā[lu] X X <g type="kaḻañcu"/> (4) ˚aṇitiraṉ colai korai cirāḷ</p><p>(4) X [ṉ]c cātti ˚avaṉukku ˚āka ˚aṇitiraṉ colai X <g type="kaḻañcu"/> (5) tevarkku cantirātittavaṟ ˚iravum</p><p>(5) X lum ˚eriya vaitta nontāviḷakku ˚oṉ[ṟu] <g type="kaḻañcu"/> (6) vaitta cāvāmūvāp perāṭu</p><p>(6) X ṇūṟu toṇṇūṟum ˚ivai paṉmā X <g type="kaḻañcu"/> (7) <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <foreign>śva</foreign>ra ra<foreign>kṣai</foreign> ||</p><p> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> for the Lord ( <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> <foreign>ṭaiyārkku</foreign>) <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> the shepherd <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>maṉṟāṭi</foreign></supplied> Aṇitiraṉ Cōlai Muttaṉ Korai Cirāḷḷai (?) <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> who resides <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>irukkum</foreign></supplied> in this Paḻuvūr <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> was killed (? <foreign>paṭa</foreign>{{<foreign>k</foreign>}}<foreign>ola koṉṟa</foreign>) <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> Aṇitiraṉ Cōlai <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> to him <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>avaṉukku</foreign></supplied>, on behalf of <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>cātti</foreign></supplied> <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> to the god <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>tēvarkku</foreign></supplied>, as long as the sun and the moon endure, night <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>iravum</foreign></supplied> and day <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>pakalum</foreign></supplied>, gave <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>vaitta</foreign></supplied> to burn <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>eriya</foreign></supplied>; he gave <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>vaitta</foreign></supplied> for one perpetual lamp <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>nontāviḷakku oṉṟu</foreign></supplied> ninety <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>toṇṇūṟum</foreign></supplied> undying and non-ageing <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>cāvāmūvā</foreign></supplied> great goats <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>perāṭu</foreign></supplied>. They <supplied reason="explanation"><foreign>ivai</foreign></supplied> are under the protection of the Paṉmāheśvaras.</p></div>

